# TAC-O Integration Rules

## Data Handling
- All sensor data from Zeetachec is CUI -- encrypt at rest (AES-256-GCM) and in transit (TLS 1.3)
- Apply Merkle hashing to every stored observation in MINDEX
- Never log raw CUI data to stdout/console in production
- Use environment variables for all credentials and API keys

## Architecture
- Zeeta sensors -> MycoBrain (edge processing) -> MDP -> MAS (classification) -> MINDEX (storage)
- NLM inference runs at TWO tiers: Jetson edge (fast, lightweight ONNX) and server (full model)
- AVANI ecological safety check is MANDATORY before any threat alert reaches operator
- Marine mammal filter score > 0.5 gates classification for human review

## API Patterns
- Maritime endpoints follow existing patterns in fusarium_api.py and crep_stream.py
- Use WebSocket for real-time feeds, REST for queries
- FUSARIUM maritime routes: /fusarium/maritime/*
- CREP maritime routes: /crep/maritime/*
- Worldview maritime routes: /worldview/maritime/*

## Agent Patterns
- TAC-O agents live in mycosoft_mas/agents/clusters/taco/
- All agents extend BaseAgent from mycosoft_mas/agents/base_agent.py
- Register agents in agent_manager.py and cluster_manager.py
- Agent IDs use taco- prefix (e.g. taco-signal-classifier)

## NLM Patterns
- Maritime fingerprints extend existing dataclass patterns
- Maritime heads are additive to existing heads in nlm/model/heads.py
- Deterministic physics transforms (Mackenzie, Thorp, Snell) run before neural encoding
- Export models as ONNX for Jetson edge deployment

## Testing
- Every new module requires tests
- Test acoustic classification with synthetic waveforms
- Test AVANI filter with known marine mammal frequency profiles
- Test MDP protocol with mock Zeeta sensor frames

## Database
- Maritime tables: acoustic_signatures, ocean_environments, magnetic_baselines, taco_observations, taco_assessments
- All tables use PostGIS GEOGRAPHY columns for spatial queries
- Qdrant collections: acoustic_signatures (512d cosine), magnetic_anomalies (256d cosine)
